    </avalancheProblem>
    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>More moist snow slides and avalanches are possible.</highlights>
      <comment>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust and will soften during the day. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In particular on very steep slopes and in steep rocky terrain more small and, in isolated cases, medium-sized moist snow slides and avalanches are possible as the penetration by moisture increases.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>The surface of the snowpack has frozen to form a strong crust and will already soften in the late morning. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Below approximately 2500 m: The snowpack is moist and its surface has a melt-freeze crust. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> Below approximately 2400 m only a little snow is lying on south facing slopes. Above approximately 1600 m there is still a very large amount of snow on north facing slopes.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
